When a relative clause states not a mere fact about the antecedent (cf. see. 118), but defines it as having a certain quality or characteristic, the subjunctive is used and we have a relative clause of characteristic. This construction' is especially common when the antecedent is indefinite or general and needs to be defined. Compare the two sentences—

a. The soldier who tls-fleeing is afraid.

b. No one who flees is brave.

In a the relative clause merely states the fact that the soldier is fleeing; in b the thought is ‘⁴ No one of such a character that he flees is brave.” Hence the Latin ε -

a. Miles qui fugit eet timidus.

b. Nemo qui fugiat est fortia.
